# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-share-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In computing, a **hyperlink**, or simply a **link**, is a digital reference providing direct access to data by a user's clicking or tapping.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A hyperlink points to a whole document or to a specific element within a document.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The text that is linked from is known as anchor text.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A software system that is used for viewing and creating hypertext is a *hypertext system*, and to create a hyperlink is *to hyperlink* (or simply *to link*).
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A user following hyperlinks is said to *navigate* or *browse* the hypertext.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The document containing a hyperlink is known as its source document.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] For example, in content from Wikipedia or Google Search, many words and terms in the text are hyperlinked to definitions of those terms.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Hyperlinks are often used to implement reference mechanisms such as tables of contents, footnotes, bibliographies, indexes, and glossaries.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In some hypertext, hyperlinks can be bidirectional: they can be followed in two directions, so both ends act as anchors and as targets.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] More complex arrangements exist, such as many-to-many links.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Another possibility is transclusion, for which the link target is a document fragment that replaces the link anchor within the source document.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Not only persons browsing the document may follow hyperlinks.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] These hyperlinks may also be followed automatically by programs.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A program that traverses the hypertext, following each hyperlink and gathering all the retrieved documents is known as a Web *spider* or crawler.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] An inline link displays remote content without the need for embedding the content.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The remote content may be accessed with or without the user following the link.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] An inline link may display a modified version of the content; for instance, instead of an image, a thumbnail, low resolution preview, cropped section, or magnified section may be shown.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The full content is then usually available on demand, as is the case with print publishing software – e.g., with an external link.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] This allows for smaller file sizes and quicker response to changes when the full linked content is not needed, as is the case when rearranging a page layout.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] An anchor hyperlink (anchor link) is a link bound to a portion of a document, which is often called a fragment.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The fragment is generally a portion of text or a heading, though not necessarily.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] For instance, it may also be a *hot area* in an image (image map in HTML), a designated, often irregular part of an image.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Fragments are marked with *anchors* (in any of various ways), which is why a link to a fragment is called an anchor link (that is, a link to an anchor).
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] For example, in XML, the element `<anchor id="name" />"` provides anchoring capability (as long as the DTD or schema defines it), and in wiki markup, `{{anchor|name}}` is a typical example of implementing it.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In word processor apps, anchors can be inserted where desired and may be called *bookmarks*.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In URLs, the hash character (#) precedes the name of the anchor for the fragment.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] One way to define a hot area in an image is by a list of coordinates that indicate its boundaries.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] For example, a political map of Africa may have each country hyperlinked to further information about that country.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A separate invisible hot area interface allows for swapping skins or labels within the linked hot areas without repetitive embedding of links in the various skin elements.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A **fat link** (also known as a "one-to-many" link, an "extended link" or a "multi-tailed link") is a hyperlink which leads to multiple endpoints; the link is a set-valued function.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Tim Berners-Lee saw the possibility of using hyperlinks to link any information to any other information over the Internet.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Hyperlinks were therefore integral to the creation of the World Wide Web.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Web pages are written in the hypertext mark-up language HTML.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Webgraph is a graph, formed from web pages as vertices and hyperlinks, as directed edges.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The W3C recommendation called XLink describes hyperlinks that offer a far greater degree of functionality than those offered in HTML.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] These **extended links** can be *multidirectional*, remove linking from, within, and between XML documents.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] It can also describe *simple links*, which are unidirectional and therefore offer no more functionality than hyperlinks in HTML.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Permalinks are URLs that are intended to remain unchanged for many years into the future, yielding hyperlinks that are less susceptible to link rot.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Permalinks are often rendered simply, that is, as friendly URLs, so as to be easy for people to type and remember.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Permalinks are used in order to point and redirect readers to the same Web page, blog post or any online digital media.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The scientific literature is a place where link persistence is crucial to the public knowledge.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A 2013 study in BMC Bioinformatics analyzed 15,000 links in abstracts from Thomson Reuters' Web of Science citation index, founding that the median lifespan of Web pages was 9.3 years, and just 62% were archived.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The median lifespan of a Web page constitutes high-degree variable, but its order of magnitude usually is of some months.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] An *Internet shortcut* file, also known as the URL file format, has the file extension .url (possibly hidden by default in the graphical user interface), and is the file format in Windows systems used for hyperlinks to the Internet.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Internet shortcuts are text files, but their internal structure is similar to that of an INI file.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Opening them in the graphical file browser of Windows or macOS (but not Linux) will open the link in the default web browser.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Internet shortcut files can be easily made by hand, as the minimum features needed to operate as a hyperlink are simply the `[InternetShortcut]` header and the `URL=` key-value pair.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Other key-value pairs are irregularly supported across operating systems.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] On macOS systems, the specialized file format for file based hyperlinks is the .webloc file.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A file based hyperlink under Unix/Linux with a desktop environment is stored in a .desktop file.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] It is a text file with a syntax highly similar to the Windows `URL` file described above.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A link from one domain to another is said to be *outbound* from its source anchor and *inbound* to its target.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The most common destination anchor is a URL used in the World Wide Web.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] This can refer to a document, e.g. a webpage, or other resource, or to a position in a webpage.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The latter is achieved by means of an HTML element with a "name" or "id" attribute at that position of the HTML document.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The URL of the position is the URL of the webpage with a fragment identifier – "#*id attribute*" – appended.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] When linking to PDF documents from an HTML page the "*id attribute*" can be replaced with syntax that references a page number or another element of the PDF, for example, "#*page=386*".
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] A web browser usually displays a hyperlink in some distinguishing way, e.g. in a different color, font or style, or with certain symbols following to visualize link target or document types.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The behavior and style of links can be specified using the Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) language.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In a graphical user interface, the appearance of a mouse cursor may change into a hand motif to indicate a link.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In most graphical web browsers, links are displayed in underlined blue text when they have not been visited, but underlined purple text when they have.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] When the user activates the link (e.g., by clicking on it with the mouse) the browser displays the link's target.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] If the target is not an HTML file, depending on the file type and on the browser and its plugins, another program may be activated to open the file.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In a typical web browser, this would display as the underlined word "Example" in blue, which when clicked would take the user to the example.com website.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] This contributes to a clean, easy to read text or document.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Mozilla Firefox, IE, Opera, and many other web browsers all show the URL.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In addition, the URL is commonly shown in the status bar.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Normally, a link opens in the current frame or window, but sites that use frames and multiple windows for navigation can add a special "target" attribute to specify where the link loads.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] If no window exists with that name, a new window is created with the ID, which can be used to refer to the window later in the browsing session.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Creation of new windows is probably the most common use of the "target" attribute.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] To prevent accidental reuse of a window, the special window names "_blank" and "_new" are usually available, and always cause a new window to be created.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] It is especially common to see this type of link when one large website links to an external page.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The intention in that case is to ensure that the person browsing is aware that there is no endorsement of the site being linked to by the site that was linked from.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] However, the attribute is sometimes overused and can sometimes cause many windows to be created even while browsing a single site.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Another special page name is "_top", which causes any frames in the current window to be cleared away so that browsing can continue in the full window.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The term "link" was coined in 1965 (or possibly 1964) by Ted Nelson at the start of Project Xanadu.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Nelson had been inspired by "As We May Think", a popular 1945 essay by Vannevar Bush.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In the essay, Bush described a microfilm-based machine (the Memex) in which one could link any two pages of information into a "trail" of related information, and then scroll back and forth among pages in a trail as if they were on a single microfilm reel.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Though Nelson's Xanadu Corporation was eventually funded by Autodesk in the 1980s, it never created this proprietary public-access network.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Meanwhile, working independently, a team led by Douglas Engelbart (with Jeff Rulifson as chief programmer) was the first to implement the hyperlink concept for scrolling within a single document (1966), and soon after for connecting between paragraphs within separate documents (1968), with NLS.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Ben Shneiderman working with graduate student Dan Ostroff designed and implemented the highlighted link in the HyperTIES system in 1983.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] HyperTIES was used to produce the world's first electronic journal, the July 1988 Communications of the ACM, which was cited as the source for the link concept in Tim Berners-Lee's Spring 1989 manifesto for the Web.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In 1988, Ben Shneiderman and Greg Kearsley used HyperTIES to publish "Hypertext Hands-On!", the world's first electronic book.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Released in 1987 for the Apple Macintosh, the database program HyperCard allowed for hyperlinking between various pages within a document, as well as to other documents and separate applications on the same computer.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The first widely used open protocol that included hyperlinks from any Internet site to any other Internet site was the Gopher protocol from 1991.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] It was soon eclipsed by HTML after the 1993 release of the Mosaic browser (which could handle Gopher links as well as HTML links).
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] HTML's advantage was the ability to mix graphics, text, and hyperlinks, unlike Gopher, which just had menu-structured text and hyperlinks.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] While hyperlinking among webpages is an intrinsic feature of the web, some websites object to being linked by other websites; some have claimed that linking to them is not allowed without permission.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In certain jurisdictions, it is or has been held that hyperlinks are not merely references or citations, but are devices for copying web pages.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In the Netherlands, Karin Spaink was initially convicted in this way of copyright infringement by linking, although this ruling was overturned in 2003.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] The courts that advocate this view see the mere publication of a hyperlink that connects to illegal material to be an illegal act in itself, regardless of whether referencing illegal material is illegal.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In 2000, British Telecom sued Prodigy, claiming that Prodigy infringed its patent (U.S. patent 4,873,662) on web hyperlinks.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] After litigation, a court found for Prodigy, ruling that British Telecom's patent did not cover web hyperlinks.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] In United States *jurisprudence*, there is a distinction between the mere act of linking to someone else's website, and linking to content that is illegal (e.g., gambling illegal in the US) or infringing (e.g., illegal MP3 copies).
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Several courts have found that merely linking to someone else's website, even if by bypassing commercial advertising, is not copyright or trademark infringement, regardless of how much someone else might object.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Linking to illegal or infringing content can be sufficiently problematic to give rise to legal liability.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Compare for a summary of the current status of US copyright law as to hyperlinking, see the discussion regarding the *Arriba Soft* and *Perfect 10* cases.
[src:web-share-api/hyperlink] Somewhat controversially, Vuestar Technologies has tried to enforce patents applied for by its owner, Ronald Neville Langford, around the world relating to search techniques using hyperlinked images to other websites or web pages.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] The **`canShare()`** method of the `Navigator` interface returns `true` if the equivalent call to `navigator.share()` would succeed.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] The method returns `false` if the data cannot be *validated*.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] The Web Share API is gated by the web-share permission policy.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] The `canShare()` method will return `false` if the permission is supported but has not been granted.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] An object defining the share data to test.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] Typically, an object with the same properties is passed to `navigator.share()` if this call returns `true`.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] Properties that are unknown to the user agent are ignored; share data is only assessed on properties understood by the user agent.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] All properties are optional but at least one known data property must be specified or the method will return `false`.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] A string representing a URL to be shared.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] A string representing text to be shared.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] A string representing the title to be shared.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] An array of `File` objects representing files to be shared.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] Returns `true` if the specified `data` can be shared with `Navigator.share()`, otherwise `false`.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] The example uses `navigator.canShare()` to check whether `navigator.share()` can share the specified data.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] The HTML just creates a paragraph in which to display the result of the test.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] This method feature tests whether a particular data property is valid and shareable.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] If used with a single `data` property it will return `true` only if that property is valid and can be shared on the platform.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-canshare] The code below demonstrates verifying that a data property is supported.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The **`share()`** method of the `Navigator` interface invokes the native sharing mechanism of the device to share data such as text, URLs, or files.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The available *share targets* depend on the device, but might include the clipboard, contacts and email applications, websites, Bluetooth, etc.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The method resolves a `Promise` with `undefined`.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] On Windows this happens when the share popup is launched, while on Android the promise resolves once the data has successfully been passed to the *share target*.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The `share()` method will throw exceptions if the permission is supported but has not been granted.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] All properties are optional but at least one known data property must be specified.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] A string representing a title to be shared.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] A `Promise` that resolves with `undefined`, or rejected with one of the Exceptions given below.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The document is not fully active, or other sharing operations are in progress.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] A `web-share` Permissions Policy has been used to block the use of this feature, the window does not have transient activation, or a file share is being blocked due to security considerations.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The specified share data cannot be validated.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The user canceled the share operation or there are no share targets available.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] There was a problem starting the share target or transmitting the data.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The following is a list of usually shareable file types.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] However, you should always test with `navigator.canShare()` if sharing would succeed.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] This method requires that the current document have the web-share Permissions Policy and transient activation.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] (It must be triggered off a UI event like a button click and cannot be launched at arbitrary points by a script.) Further, the method must specify valid data that is supported for sharing by the native implementation.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The example below shows a button click invoking the Web Share API to share MDN's URL.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] This is taken from our Web share test (see the source code).
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] The HTML just creates a button to trigger the share, and a paragraph in which to display the result of the test.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] Click the button to launch the share dialog on your platform.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] Text will appear below the button to indicate whether the share was successful or provide an error code.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] To share files, first test for and call `navigator.canShare()`.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] Then include the list of files in the call to `navigator.share()`.
[src:web-share-api/navigator-share] Note that the data object passed to the `navigator.canShare()` only includes the `files` property, as the `title` and `text` shouldn't matter.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] Application sharing is the ability of one application to pass information or data to another application on the same device.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] This feature is useful for users as it allows them to share information between two applications without the need for these applications to have prior knowledge of each other.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] For example, on your mobile device, you can share photos or videos from your photo app with another application that accepts images, such as an email application.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The operating system selects the list of applications that are able to handle the shared image data and displays them to the user.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] Once the user selects one of the target applications, the operating system launches it with the shared image.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] Progressive Web Apps (PWAs) also have the ability to share information using the same OS-orchestrated pattern.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] PWAs can both share data and accept shared data.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] When building a PWA, accepting shared data can make your PWA feel more familiar and naturally integrated into your user's devices.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] To make it possible for users to share data with other apps from your PWA, use the Web Share API.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The Web Share API allows your app to share text, links, or files with other apps via the underlying operating system share mechanism.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] To share data, use the `navigator.share()` method in response to a user action, such as a button click.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] Before displaying content-sharing UI in your application, check to ensure the Web Share API feature is supported.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] Even the browsers that support the Web Share API don't all support sharing all types of data.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] Therefore, it's a good practice to use the `navigator.canShare()` method first to validate whether the data you intend to share is, indeed, shareable from the browser that's running your app.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The `navigator.share()` method returns a `Promise` that may be rejected in cases such as when the shared data is incorrect, when the user aborts the share operation, or when the data transmission failed.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] It's therefore important to catch the promise rejection in order to avoid errors in your app's JavaScript code.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The following example demonstrates how to share a link and some text when a button in the app is clicked.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The `canBrowserShareData` function used in the example is described in Checking for support and not repeated here.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The following code example demonstrates how to share a file when a button in the app is clicked.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The `canBrowserShareFiles` function is used to display the share button only if the browser supports sharing files.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] For more information, see the sharing files example on the `navigator.share()` method page.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] To register your PWA as a target of other apps' shared data, use the Web Share Target API and, in particular, the `share_target` web app manifest member.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The `share_target` manifest member allows an installed PWA to be registered, at the operating system level, as a potential target for content shared by other apps.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] This means that when a user shares some data that's compatible with your PWA, from another app, the operating system will list your PWA alongside other typical share targets like email or messaging apps.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] Note that the PWA must be installed to be displayed as a potential target for receiving shared data.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The information you provide with the `share_target` member, in your manifest file, defines which data your app can be a target for, and how the operating system should launch your app when the user selects it as the target.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] When your app is selected by the user to handle another apps' shared content, your app is launched and the shared content is passed to it in a similar way to that in which `<form>` elements are submitted.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] In the previous web app manifest code example, when the ChattyBox app is selected as a target, it is launched by making an HTTP `GET` request at the `/share-handler` URL, with the shared data passed as request parameters named `description` and `link`.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The `GET` request will look like this: `/shared-handler?description=...&link=...`.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] For more information, see the example Receive share data using GET on the `share_target` web app manifest member page.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] In the previous example, text data was handled as a `GET` request.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] However, handling files requires the use of a `POST` request with a `multipart/form-data` encoding type.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] As this example shows, each file object in the `files` property must have a `name` property and an `accept` property.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] The `accept` property must specify the accepted MIME types or file extensions.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] When the app is selected by the user to handle a shared file (or files), the app is launched with a `POST` request at the `/share-file-handler` URL, with encoded form data.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] Because this is a `POST` request, your app's main JavaScript code can't access the form data directly.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] You can handle the submitted files in your server-side code, by receiving them at the `/share-file-handler` URL end point.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] In this code example, the shared files are extracted from the form data and the user is redirected to a different page.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] It's up to you, using the code in your service worker, to handle the extracted files as you want.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] For example, you can send them to your app's main JavaScript code using the `Worker.postMessage()` method or store them in an Indexed DB database which can be accessed both by your service worker and app's main JavaScript code.
[src:web-share-api/share-data-between-apps] For more information, see the receiving shared files example on the `share_target` web app manifest member page.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Apart from obvious instances, which can be observed in human activity, many examples can be found in nature.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] When an organism takes in nutrition or oxygen, for instance, its internal organs are designed to divide and distribute the energy taken in, to supply parts of its body that need it.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Flowers divide and distribute their seeds.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] In a broader sense, it can also include free granting of use rights to goods that can be treated as nonrival goods, such as information.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] File sharing is the practice of distributing or providing access to digitally stored information, such as computer programs, multi-media (audio, video), documents, or electronic books.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] It may be implemented through a variety of ways.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Sharing is a key feature in the developing field of free software and open source software, with implications for economics.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] This is leading to a need to review licensing, patents and copyright, and to controversy in these areas, as well as new approaches like Creative Commons and the GNU General Public License.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Furthermore, sharing is a key feature of Internet culture in which images, videos, links, knowledge and other content are shared on Web 2.0-platforms such as reddit.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Andreas Wittel said that in the modern, Internet-era discourse "Sharing now is associated with politics, with socialist, communist, and anarchist values, with the free culture movement and the digital commons" and it "is an expression of a Utopian imaginary".
[src:web-share-api/sharing] In computer science, the issue of handling shared resources figures prominently.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] For example, time-sharing is an approach to interactive computing in which a single computer is used to provide apparently simultaneous interactive general-purpose computing to multiple users by sharing processor time.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Sharing of resources between processes and threads is the source of most of the difficulties of concurrent programming.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] The word "sharing" is also used in some functional programming communities to refer specifically to sharing of memory between different data items to save space, otherwise known as hash consing.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Resource sharing—called *kaláka* in Hungarian—is an old tradition in Hungary.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Young couples had to build their house after marriage.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Marriage itself was called *házasodás* in Hungarian (en: becoming the owner of a house).
[src:web-share-api/sharing] When doing so, the whole community, relatives and acquaintances helped the young couple with work, knowledge and even money.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] At pigsticking, all members of the community got their shares too.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Superfluous plants were freely distributed to neighbours in the season.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] In most cultures, members of the same household tend to pool their resources.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] In the New Testament, John the Baptist commended sharing as the mark of a new way of life: "If you have two shirts, share with the person who does not have one.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Market sharing occurs when competitors agree to divide or allocate customers, suppliers or territories among themselves rather than allowing competitive market forces to work.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Market sharing is generally an illegal practice as it violates antitrust laws and the basic principles of the free market.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Market sharing mainly occur in the form of cartels like the Guadalajara Cartel, which was the first Mexican drug cartel to consolidate the production and supply of illegal marijuana into a single organization.
[src:web-share-api/sharing] Sharing in a market may also refer to the temporary or permanent transfer of information and other physical as well as intellectual property, but this is generally accompanied by the exchange of money.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] The **Web Share API** provides a mechanism for sharing text, links, files, and other content to an arbitrary *share target* selected by the user.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] The **Web Share API** allows a site to share text, links, files, and other content to user-selected share targets, utilizing the sharing mechanisms of the underlying operating system.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] These share targets typically include the system clipboard, email, contacts or messaging applications, and Bluetooth or Wi-Fi channels.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] The `navigator.canShare()` method may be used to first validate whether some data is "shareable", prior to passing it to `navigator.share()` for sending.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] The `navigator.share()` method invokes the native sharing mechanism of the underlying operating system and passes the specified data.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] It requires transient activation, and hence must be triggered off a UI event like a button click.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] Further, the method must specify valid data that is supported for sharing by the native implementation.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] The Web Share API is gated by the web-share Permissions Policy.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] If the policy is supported but has not been granted, both methods will indicate that the data is not shareable.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] Returns a boolean indicating whether the specified data is shareable.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] Returns a `Promise` that resolves if the passed data was successfully sent to a share target.
[src:web-share-api/web-share-api] This method must be called on a button click or other user activation (requires transient activation).
